resources.string: This user can log into any device. Changing the profile requires an internet connection
This user can only log into this device/local deployment.
This information requires an online session to change! Please change the information on the web interface, or wait until this device is back online
This policy can be overridden by a user with the "Override" policy applied to their account
The policy system will allow the user to override this policy decision
The user cannot override the policy decision
This identifier type requires a check digit - if you are entering an existing identifier be sure to include the check digit information here

The object identifier of the identity domain is used by HL7v3 messages and HL7v2 messages to tag an identifier with the identity domain to which the identity domain belongs. These should be:
  • An IANA Private Enterprise Number
  • An HL7 Registered Assigning Authority
  • A UUID in format 2.25.XXXX
Select the general classification which identifiers assigned to this identity domain carry
The namespace identifier is used in the HDSI and HL7v2 to identify the identifiers. These must be unique in this installation of SanteDB.
The human readable name of the identity domain
If this identifier only applies to specific types of resources then select the type of resources to which this identifier can be assigned
Enter the URL for this identity domains. URLs are used by FHIR for correlating the identity domain with the identifier when FHIR messages are received
Use this field to specify the format of the identifier (the pattern that conformant identifiers need to have)

Whenever an identifier in this domain is registered from this application - it can be flagged as authoritative or informative. You may restrict the ability of non-authoritative applications from issuing new identifiers (which will result in a data quality warning)
Select the policies which are required for a security principal (user, device, etc.) for identifiers in this domain to be disclosed.
If the identifier uses a separate check digit in the check digit field (or required generation), select the check digit algorithm to be used
If the identifiers in this identity domain have a specialized format (for example, check digits or computational generation) select the implementation of the validation here.
Select the citizenship(s) which the person holds
Select secondary facilities which are subscribed/interested in this entity
Select the direct parent of this entity in the entity hierarchy
This entity is a proper record. To edit it, you\'ll need to visit the object\'s detail page

Sets the state of the current object in the database:
  • NEW: The object can be used however the information may not be validated
  • ACTIVE: The object can be used normally
  • OBSOLETE: The object should no longer be used as it has been supersceded
  • NULLIFIED: The object was created in error
  • INACTIVE: The object should not be used
The primary address for the person/patient. This is the residence where the person primarily lives
The work address for the person/patient's place of employment.
A temporary address where the person/patient resides
Indicates the intended use of the address such as PhysicalVisit for a physical address, or WorkPlace, etc.
A partition of a country (also known as a Region, Territory, Zone, etc.)
A partition of a state, province, region (also known as a Division, District, Parish, etc.)
An municipal area (also known as Town, Municipality, City, Village, etc.)
A location (building number, unit number, etc.) which is used to located the address on a street or road.
A partition of a city (also a borough, division, ward/village, etc.)
A codified representation of the address used for postal delivery and/or package routing, etc.
The country where the address resides
The post-office box, mailbox number, or other identification for a delivery instruction
The unit, suite, office, or other sub-division of the building
If delivery or other mail delivered to this address carries a care-of instruction
A location which assists in the locating of the address (i.e. closes intersection, ward, etc.)
The intended use for the name. For example OfficialRecord would indicate the name is used on official documentation.
A prefix or honorary title used (example: Sir, Mr., Ms.)
Family names of the entity (or surname)
Suffixes for the name such as an enumetion (William Gates III) a designator (Joe Smith Jr.) or designated title (Dr. Fran Smith MD)
Unclassified names for the entity which cannot be classified appropriately.
Select the nature of the relationship between this entity and the entity being registered (example: Mother, Father, Brother, etc.)
Select the role of the entity playing the role here. How is this role important? (i.e. emergency contact, power of attorney, etc.)
Are you sure you want to remove this identifier from this entity?
The administrative portal has no authority to assign this identifier
A date of birth and gender are required for this operation to be completed
If the patient is known to be deceased, indicate this information and the approximate (or exact) on which the person died
If this person was born as part of a multiple birth (twin, triplet, etc.) the birthing order of this person.
Select the highest level of education which the patient has attained
Select the living arrangement that the patient is currently living under
Select the most accurate marital status of the patient
Select the religion which the patient actively practices
Select the ethnic group, or tribe to which the patient belongs
Optionally select the role that this related person plays for the patient for example: Power of Attorney (signing authority), Payment Guarantor, Emergency Contact
Select the primary facility where this patient will seek care. For programmes, this is the facility where the patient should appear in the denominator/catchment
Select facilities where the patient may visit to seek care, however should not appear on their denominator/catchment reports
Select the most appropraite occupation code for the person
Select the nationality of the person
If the person is a very important person (VIP) such as a politician, actor, or other occupation which may require additional protection, please indicate here
The date/year that the person was known to have died
Select one or more employers under which the person has active employment
Select the SanteDB classification of the place which is being created
Changing the class concept may invalidate data already present in your database. You should only change this if there are no relationships established with this place
Select the sub-classification of the place which you're creating (for example: Ward, Community Hospital, etc.)
The ISO country code for this country
Enter the official name of the place
The primary classification or type of organization that this entry represents
The legal mailing/contact address of the organization
The industry that this organization operates within
The official/legal name of the organization
Error validating code for Patient resource
Select the overall classification concept of this material. This is used by decision support and business rules to understand the classification of the material
The fully qualified name of the material as it appears in clinical documentation, regulations, product certifications, etc.
If the material is commonly referred to a shorter name, enter it here. This is the common name by which the material is known
Select the format in which the material is packaged or administered (such as injection, drops, etc.)
The number and unit of one dose unit which represents one dose of the product
Select the real-world units in which the material is administered, prescribed or ordered. Examples: Dose, Puffs, etc.
Enter any special long-form documentation about the material including how it is administered, any safety or regulatory concerns, etc.
If this material is a subclass of another material then enter the parent material. For example, an mRNA COVID vaccine <c>IS A</c> COVID vaccine

If this material is composed of multiple attributes of other materials, then the parts should be listed here. For example, a MMRV vaccination material may have parts consisting of a Varicella, Measles, Rubella and Mumps materials
You can select one or more conditions or problems that this material is used commonly to treat or prevent
If the use of this material requires the use of another material (such as a syringe, diluent, etc.) select the materials which are used here
Select the regulatory body which is in charge of this material, or should be notified for further investigation when safety concerns arise from use of the material
Enter one or more authorized manufacturers or sources of supply which are licensed to produce the material
Select the regulatory expiration of this product type/material (when the material is no longer used)
Select the classification / type code for this material (if it is different than the parent kind)
Enter the quantity (amount of material) which is in one unit of this product used for ordering stock
Enter the common name or trade name for the manufactured product
Select the kind of material which this instance of the material represents
Select the organization which manufactures this product. This should represent the manufacturer of origin rather than the supplier
For every one of the current product, how many of the type of material is represented

Indicates that the material can be administered to a patient or subject. Examples:
  • Enable for medications, vaccines, solutions, medical devices, etc.
  • Disable for syringes, pill bottles, containers, diluents, etc.
The lot or batch number of the specified product type
The latest date where the material maintains its potentcy
Select the product which this lot number is an instance of
Check this box to indicate that the facility is not fixed (for example: a portable facility, vehicle or bus) as opposed to a building
This facility record represents a mobile care facility (such as ambulance, mobile clinic, etc.)

Select the type of scheduling instruction which should be registered for this job. The types of schedule are:
  • None - The job will never be started on a schedule
  • Calendar Schedule - The job will start on the specified date, at the specified time, on the specified days
  • Regular Interval - The job will run every X hours, minutes, or days
This job is not scheduled to run automatically. It will only run when initiated by a user
This job is scheduled to run on an interval. Interval jobs are run every X seconds/minutes/hours regardless of the day or time
This job is set on a calendar schedule. Calendar schedule jobs will run on the specified days from the specified start date at the specified time
This schedule will start on the specified date
The time of day when the schedule is to be executed
The days of the week to repeat this schedule
Indicates the repetition of this job
Identifies the classification of the event
Identifies the time when this event occurred
Identifies the location where this event is being recorded/occurred
The person/people who were responsible for recording/reporting the event
The date on which the newborn was born
The established gender of the newborn
If this newborn was part of a multiple birth (twin, triplet, etc.)
The place (hospital, township, etc.) where the newborn was born
The unique identifier for this matching configuration file.

The resource types (like Patient, Person, etc.) which this match configuration can be used for. The Master Data Management layer will use this information to determine which matching configurations to use

Optional tags which are used by the SanteDB iCDR and other plugins to determine how to handle matches of this configuration. Common tags are
  • $mdm.auto-link - Instruct MDM to automatically link the matches which meet the Match threshold without human intervention
Enter a description for your match configuration
When classifying the result - the absolute scores will be used for classification
When classifying the result - the relative % score will be used for classification
Indicates the maximum number of records to load into memory from the database before matching commences.
The lower this number is, the more round-trips to the database are required

Indicates the method that the results from this block set will be incorporated into the previous.
  • INTERSECT WITH - Records in this block must also appear in the previous block
  • UNION WITH - Records in this block which have to previously appeared will be included
Indicates the query statements which will be sent to the database or other physical store. These are in HDSI format
A refernce identifier which this scoring attribute can be referenced by (recommended)
The access properties which are used to retrieve data from the $input and blocked record. These are in HDSI format
In record linkage the M value describes the likelihood that, when two values agree, they represent a definite match.
In record linkage the U value describes the likelihood that, when two values agree, they agreed by complete coincidence.
The match weight is the computed weighting for this attribute which is added to the candidates score when the assertions agree. The value is derived from ln(m / u) / ln(2.0)
The non-match weight is a computed weighting for this attribute which is added to the candidate\'s score when the assertions disagree (fail). The value is derived from ln((1 - m) / (1 - u)) / ln(2.0)
Indicates the action which should be taken when the input or blocked record do not have a value populated at property
The entire candidate match pair is disqualified from consideration as a match
The attribute is removed from consideration (note: this reduces the total possible score)
The attribute is scored as though the missing recrd would have matched
The attribute is scored as though the missing record would not have matched
The attribute assertions continue to be executed (most likely this results in a non-match score)
The attribute is scored as 0 rather than the non-match score

When the attribute specifies an evaluation guard the guard attributes must
  • Have been evaluated successfully
  • Match the criteria specified
Otherwise the whenNull action is taken.
These are comments/notes by the author of the match configuration which provide context to this scoring block

The assertions to make on this object - before running the data can be transformed using one or more transformation attributes. Transforms are:
  • Unary - Applied against the $input and $blocked resulting in new $input and $blocked records (like soundex, levenshtein, etc.)
  • Binary - Applied against the $input and $blocked and return a single result
When specified, the partial weight will multiply the calculated match or non-match weight by the algorithm selected in the dropdown.
Provide a unique name for the subscription. The name is used internally to identify the subscription data
Provide a brief description of the subscription. Include information such as what the subscription does, what is its purpose, etc. For example: Send deceased patient demographics to CRVS system
Select the type of resource (RIM resource) that this subscription operates on
Select one or more events (which occur on the Applies To resource) when the notification should be sent
Provide a support contact (telephone, e-mail, etc.) for this subscription. This can be used for diagnosing connectivity
Provide one or more filter criteria (which evaluate to true) when this subscription should be triggered (i.e. when should SanteDB send the notification to the remote endpoint)
Indicates a date/time when this subscription will become active
Indicates a date/time when this subscription will cease to be active

The remote endpoint where notifications for this subscription should be sent. If selecting OTHER as the dispatcher type, the scheme of the URL is used, samples:
  • sms:// - use the SMS dispatcher
  • mailto: - use the e-mail dispatcher
  • llp:// - use the HL7v2 dispacher
Identifies the type of messaging format to be used to send the notification (for example: FHIR messages, FHIR rest hook, HL7v2, etc.). OTHER is used when the iCDR has a dispatcher not listed here
Additional settings (key/value pairs) which are used be the dispatcher to control the flow of information. For example, in FHIR these equate to HTTP headers
Scheduled (will be run next time imports are processed)
Completed with Errors (check issues and reject file)
Provide a short, human-readable name for the code system.

Provide the code system unique object identifier. This is usually provided by the external solution consuming the reference term codes. The OID should be:
  • An IANA Private Enterprise Number (1.3...)
  • A UUID in the form 2.25.XXXXXXXX
  • An HL7 Registered OID in form 2.16.xxxxx
This is used in HL7v3 and CDA messages.
Provide the unique URL which the code system defines (or the URL the external trading partner recognizes). This is often used in HL7 FHIR messages
Provide a UNIQUE domain name for the code system (or the mnemonic defined by the external trading partner). This is often used by the HL7v2 message handler.
Provide detailed description of the code system (how it is used, the standards or interface, etc.)
The version of the code system in which the reference terms are held
How the reference term will appear when external systems request data from this terminology. For example: 11019-3, F
Official translation(s) of this reference terminology (how it will be shown in external messages)
Terms which are used in the internal SanteDB concept dictionary which this term is linked to

Mnemonics in the SanteDB concept dictionary must be globally UNIQUE, whereas reference term mnemonics are unique within their code system. It is highly recommended administrators create a globally unique mnemonic for any new concepts
Provide a short, descriptive name of what this collection of concepts contains
Provide a unique ID for this set of concepts
If the concept set has an external definition, provide the unique resource pointer to that location
Provide a long-form description of the intended use of the concept set.
Provide a unique IANA PEN, HL7 OID or use 2.25.XXXXXX to uniquely identify this concept set

The concept mnemonic is a unique, human readable name for the concept. These must be unique in the entire SanteDB instance. Try to use a consistent pattern such as type-concept for example Gender-Female
The classification allows SanteDB to understand the broad use or meaning of the concept
The name which will appear in the user interfaces
The groupings of sets to which this concept belongs.
The wire-level terms which should be used for this concept
A descriptive name which also serves as an identifier for the library in the master CDSS library
Enter a dotted identifier which serves as a universally unique identification for the library when referenced by other libraries in the master CDSS solution
The dotted object identifier (OID) for the library which is used when this CDSS library is referenced by external systems
The business version (informational version) for the library contents. This must be a semantic version in the format <c>major.minor.revision[-special]</c>
The name of the primary author (or a copyright statement)
A long-form description of the contents of the CDSS library including its purpose, what it contains, etc.
A unique identifier for the data quality rule - this is a system mnemonic for the rule
A human-readable name for the data quality rule
When a rule is active, all incoming resources specified in the rule are validated using the assertions specified
Select the type of resource to which this rule set applies. To change the resource type, all assertions must be removed
Provide a unique identifier for this assertion. When this assertion fails, this identifier will be placed on the DetectedIssue.id field
Human readable text for the assertion. When this assertion fails, this text will be placed on the DetectedIssue.text field

Indicates the severity of the detected issue that is raised when the assertion fails.
  • Error: The detected issue will result in a rejected resource/failed operation
  • Warning:: The detected issue will result in a warning. The resource may still be processed
  • Information: The detected issue will be displayed/conveyed as an informational message

Provide the HDSI expressions which will trigger this detected issue to be raised. The evaluation of multiple HDSI expressions is controlled by the selection of all-of, any-of, none-of representing logical and, or, not respectively

The backup location where this backup resides:

  • Private - Private storage (usually within the app's own data storage)
  • Public - A public location on the primary disk of this device
  • External Public - A public location on the first removable media device (usually the SD card slot)
Select this option if you would like to encrypt this backup file
The passphrase for the backup. This passphrase will need to be entered to restore the backup
Indicates the nature of the relationship between the two concepts
The concept which is the target of this relationship
